{"ts":"2026-06-27T17:54:05.026Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Current Understanding**\n\nOkay, this is excellent! I've been thinking about the suggestion to enforce frontend role visibility based on the backend's user information, ensuring the backend stays the source of truth. My recent thoughts are on the current frontend implementation; I'm curious about the specific methods used currently. I want to build on a solid foundation! I've been checking the 'app' directory, specifically.\n\n\n**Analyzing Frontend Logic**\n\nI'm focused on the frontend's role-based rendering, particularly in `/admin/clients/page.tsx`. I see conditional rendering of buttons based on the `isPlatformAdmin` flag. This flag is derived directly from the `currentUser` object fetched from the backend, specifically looking at the `role` property. I've also identified conditional actions column components, likewise gated by the same flag.\n\n\n**Examining User Role Implementations**\n\nI'm digging deeper into how user roles are implemented in the admin interfaces. For instance, in `app/admin/users/page.tsx`, the `isPlatformAdmin` flag is checked to display the \"PROVISION NEW IDENTITY\" button. The flag is determined using `currentUser?.role === \"gff_admin\"`, and this seems to be the main mechanism. I also see conditional rendering within the Inspector column, with similar access control.\n\n\n**Investigating Button Logic**\n\nI'm now closely examining the button logic within the admin interface, specifically the \"Administrative Commands\" section, focusing on how user status and key rotation are handled. I'm taking a look at `handleToggleStatus` and `handleResetCredentials` functions. I'm paying attention to the conditional rendering for the button text (Activate/Deactivate) based on the user's status, and the disabling of the \"Rotate key\" button during the reset process.\n\n\n**Evaluating Role Modification**\n\nI'm now looking at the component responsible for modifying user roles, specifically the `<select>` element. It presents role options: \"GFF Admin,\" \"Client Admin,\" and \"Client Member.\" I'm also considering the button for user deletion. I'm focusing on the `handleRoleChange` and `handleDeleteUser` functions and how they interact with the backend to enforce the role changes and user deletion.\n\n\n"}}
